The SEC meetings happened in Destin, Florida and the SEC decided to not go with to a 9 game conference schedule, they will stick to the current 8 game schedule. 

SEC commissioner Greg Sankey claims that the conference had a look at over 40 different scheduling models for the conference heading into next season when they add Texas and Oklahoma to the league
To me – adding a ninth game is the only thing that adds up. 

The arguments for keeping an 8 game schedule are injuries (team is going to play a game anyways), and that they want to keep their weaker schedules for a higher chance of making the new 12 team playoff.

Here’s why the decision to stick with an 8 game schedule is the wrong one 👀

The SEC needs to go to a 9 game conference slate, and rather than have some teams in the conference play only every 4 years. If I’m an SEC team, I want to face everyone at home and away as much as possible. That’s part of being in the best league in college football.

Jeff Brohm returns to his alma mater and hometown to lead the Louisville Cardinals football program after an extremely successful tenure at Purdue. He’s off to a red-hot start. 

Every team who transitions head coaches will have a good amount of players both entering and exiting the program, the one we have all heard about being Colorado.

The same is the case at U of L, adding 19 players and losing 25, but the quality of players they brought in is HIGH.

Louisville added HIGH-quality talent to their defense at all 3 levels. The Cardinals’ defense will be totally revamped with productive power 5 – could be up to 9 players we see good minutes from out of the portal on defense. 

Offensively, the Cardinals added a ton of talent. At WR they picked up FIVE transfers to battle it out. They picked up 2 quality starters at tackle, and another good piece inside at Guard. 

The player I’m most excited about? Transfer QB Jack Plummer from Cal. Plummer previously played for Coach Brohm, and the pair have already had a ton of success together where Plummer put up nearly 3500 passing yards, 26 touchdowns, and just 10 interceptions in their final 3 years together. 
Look for Louisville to be a contender, and quite possibly the best transfer class in the country.

Nick Saban is NOT happy about the current state of college football… let’s break it down.

Saban, one of the most respected voices in college football, warned us all at the SEC’s annual meetings, saying, ‘If you think there’s the disparity in college football now, there’s going to be a lot more in the future.’ 

He’s talking about NIL - Name, Image, and Likeness, where players can make money from their own branding. Sounds great, right? 

Well, Saban worries this could become an outsourced version of pay-for-play, with some players getting six to seven figures for appearances and social media posts.

Picture this: a college football world where the field isn’t level because some people are willing to spend more than others. To give you an idea, Tennessee’s freshman QB, Nico Iamaleava, signed a deal that will pay him $8 million over four years! 

Without a cap, like in the NFL, we could see huge budget disparities from school to school, making college football even more lopsided. So what does Saban suggest? Make it like the NFL: unionize it, cap it, level the playing field.

#cfb #collegefootball #nicksaban #alabamafootball #secfootball

I was a 5-star high school football recruit.

But I would’ve been a lot better and got a whole lot more offers if I paid attention to this one part of my training. 

SLEEP.

I got told a lot that “sleep is important” when I was playing, but I didn’t listen as well as I should have. I just took it as another story. 

Today we have data, and these findings are insane. 

A study by the University of Pittsburgh found that football players who slept an average of 8.5 hours per night for 7 weeks had significantly improved reaction times, accuracy, and sprint times.

A study by the University of California, Berkeley found that football players who were sleep-deprived made more mistakes on cognitive tests and were more likely to be injured during games.

A huge factor in causing sleep deprivation is sleep apnea. Athletes are at a way higher risk for it, but the solutions aren’t talked about enough.

@loftasleep provides an at-home sleep test so you can find out if you have sleep apnea.

Don’t take chances like I did when it comes to your sleep.

This college football coach just suspended his entire team.

Why?

A rapper shot a music video in their locker room without permission.

It happened at Florida A&M — where all football activities were suspended after rapper Real Boston Richey shot a music video in the team’s locker room with the players. 

FAMU Coach Willie Simmons had this to say about the suspension…

“The video contained graphic language that is not consistent with Florida A&M’s core values, principles, and beliefs and an internal investigation is underway to determine who authorized the use of not only the athletic facility at Galimore-Powell, but also licensed apparel that potentially violates university branding and licensing agreements.”

Coach Simmons later clarified that the players’ involvement in the video does not violate NCAA rules.

Lessons I’ve learned this year…

Most people fail because they quit. Consistency is the differentiator.

No one’s actually thinking about you as much as you think they are.

There’s no short cut. Hard work is the only way.

Toughness is showing up every day even when you don’t feel like it. Toughness is a choice.

Success is much better when you’re doing it with people you love.

The great ones aren’t different than anyone else, they just think different than every one else.

Usually the worst things in life happen to you right before amazing things happen. 

A true friend is someone who is genuinely happy when good things happen to you — not jealous or wondering why it’s not happening to them.

No one succeeds all by themselves.

Knowing when to pivot is key. 

Steve Keim made the choice to pivot after picking Josh Rosen in 2018. 

Here’s what he had to say about his decision. 

“Don’t get me wrong it hurts it’s not what you want to do financially, obviously wastes a draft pick. So it doesn’t look good it doesn’t feel good. At the same time, it’s your opportunity to make things right. You have an obligation and what is your obligation? It’s doing what’s best for the organization.”

Beau Pribula’s recruitment was WILD. 

Some coaches thought he would play safety in college. 

Up until his sophomore year of high school, he never played a snap at QB. 

“It was kind of up in the air after my sophomore year whether I’ll be a quarterback or an athlete.”

So how did he end up being a quarterback at Penn State? 

“After my sophomore year, which is when Covid hit, I got a lot of interest from Power 5 schools, they offered me and Penn State offered me.”

That decision was made going into his junior year. 

“After my junior year where I kind of flipped the switch and really took quarterback to a new level and really focusing and getting smarter in concepts.” 

@nextupwithadam #cfb #collegefootball #pennstatefootball

I spent nearly a decade in college football weight rooms, first as a player and later as a coach. Allow me to share three of the most legendary NFL weight room tales I’ve come across.

1 — Walter Payton’s Deadlift:

There’s a well-known tale about the greatest running back ever: anyone who attempted to match him in hill sprints at his Mississippi home would inevitably end up puking. 

While that’s impressive, it pales in comparison to lifting 625 pounds in a deadlift when you only weigh 208 pounds. 

Clyde Emrich, the Chicago Bears strength coach, vouches that Payton achieved this feat during his prime.

2 — Terry Long’s Squat:

Seeking to grab the attention of NFL teams in 1983 after his time at East Carolina, Terry participated in his sole powerlifting meet. 

And his stats were astonishing: an 837-pound squat, a 501-pound bench press, and an almost world-record-breaking 865-pound deadlift.

3 — The Ultimate Legend: Larry Allen’s Bench Press:

Larry Allen wasn’t just an exceptional offensive lineman for the Cowboys with a room full of trophies; he also had a bench press record of 705 pounds. 

Rumor has it that in 1998, he was close to setting the world record at 715 pounds. 

Imagine being a Super Bowl Champion and a potential world record bench press holder simultaneously.
